When you add a CircleCollider2D to the Agent and it interferes with the Ray Perception Sensor 2D, it might happen because the raycasts are detecting the CircleCollider2D of the agent itself.

To fix this, you need to add the Agent and the objects it should interact with to separate layers and then configure the Ray Perception Sensor 2D to ignore the Agent's layer.

Here's how to do that:

1. Create a new layer for your agent in the Unity Editor:

Go to Edit > Project Settings > Tags and Layers, and add a new layer named "AgentLayer" under the Layers section.

2. Assign the agent GameObject to the "AgentLayer":

Click on the agent GameObject in the hierarchy, then go to the Inspector and set the Layer dropdown to "AgentLayer."

3. Update the agent's CircleCollider2D and set the ContactFilter2D's layer mask to ignore the "AgentLayer":

In your agent's script, add the following code in the `Start()` method:

```csharp
// Update CircleCollider2D LayerMask to ignore "AgentLayer"
var circleCollider = GetComponent<CircleCollider2D>();
if (circleCollider != null)
{
    ContactFilter2D filter = new ContactFilter2D();
    filter.SetLayerMask(~LayerMask.GetMask("AgentLayer")); // Set LayerMask to ignore "AgentLayer"
    filter.useLayerMask = true;

    circleCollider.contactFilter = filter;
}
```

4. After these changes, the agent's raycast sensor should ignore its own CircleCollider2D when casting rays.

Remember to assign the correct layers to the objects that the agent should interact or detect using its Ray Perception Sensor 2D. Ensure that the RayPerceptionSensorComponent2D component only interacts with the layers you want it to detect. You can set this up by clicking on the Agent, selecting its RayPerceptionSensorComponent2D component, and configuring its Layer Mask property.

